 the\nA. F. of L., giving that organisa\ntion jurisdiction ever mea and\nwomen employed in a trade or call\ning, the A. F. of L. enters into a\nsolemn covenant with that organ\nization to which the charter is\nI granted. It gives It jurisdiction) it\nrecognises its authority; It clothes\nit with the power of absolute au\ntonomy. And having granted these\nrights to a chartered organisation\nthe A. F. of L. is under obligation\n1 to support that organisation In the\nexercise of its jurdisictional and\nI autonomous rights.\n\"This covenant between the\nAmerican Federation of Labor and\nthe United Mine Workers at Aaer\nica was signed by my distinguished\nI predecessor, the late Samuel Oom\npers, and the members of the Ena\nj cutive Council. It comas to us as a\ncovenant supported by the honor\nof the A. F. of L. and so far as 1\nam concerned, as the official\nspokesman of the toiling masses of\nour country, tho covenant made in\ni860 vriU be observed.\n\"I have spoken in this emphatic\nway, this solemn and direct way,\nbecause I feel that the occasion\ncalls for plain speaking and sim\nple, direct language. I want no\none to misunderstand the attitude\nof the A. F. of L.\u201d\nPresident Green reminded the\nconvention that the coal operators\nare the only ones who profit by\ndivision.\n\"Our position is no different\nfrom other groups,\u201d lie said, \"So\noeaaion la not recognised anywlere\nor any plaeo. Slaty yearn ago many\nprecious lives were lost in America\nto preserve the Union and the Un\nion waa preserved. And that has\never been the attitude of group# of\npeople who realise that the nation\nal and economic solidarity is es\nsential to success.\"\nThe speaker declared that a\nchange from our proaent policy\nwould result in chaos. \"Every one\nwho thought ho hod a grievance\nwould go out and start a new\nonion of his own,\" said Mr. Green,\nwho pointed out that white the A.\nF. at L. rigidly hold to thia policy,\nthe Federation stands ready to as\nsist in mediating differences, but\ncan not do so unless called upon by\nthe recognised and chartered af\nfiliate.\n\"Sometimes we ere compelled to\nstand by and watch with exceeding\ndisappointment internal rtiuggleo\nbut wa have to stand and wait to\nbe helpful. That has been our attl\ntude in every ease and It is our\nattitude toward the United Mine\n_... _:_\nUOAt IWTK1\ntu Pulaski Onatf Curt.\nI. A. W\u00bbM ui A C\nTrii\u2014. MUImw.\nHo(le\u00ab U hereby ft**u M fWf\u00bb\u2014A Ik\nlot >1 of the Ante of tbt ObMnl Amm\nbfy of UlM J A. wool bad A. 0.\nHoff* a. Traitw, itMi owoon la fas, A\n\u2022lock Three 'll Dolton Addition to Worth\nUtUo Rook. Arkansas, fttetf ioaaary HU,\nIf90, their petmoo to the ruioikl County\nCourt, preytnf that said block la aoltf Ad\ndition be reduced to acreofe tn the \u2022>in\nner and for the tarpooao eet forth ta\nwid Act 01.\nThU the nth day of Jaaaary, tm\nw a ItOOKFS, County clerk.\nPulaski county. Arbff.\n\u25a0y L. W. Adaai. D. O.\nPAINFUL CORNS\nLooms\u2014lift Oet\nA Uttit known Jemn herb, the\nLscovery of an eminent German\nscientist (Dr. Sticlnl) instantly\nsoothes the com, catlona or wait,\nthen loosen* it to that shortly yon\ncan hit it right oat This new\ndiscovery called \u201cCorn Fly\" eacitcs\nthe white blood corpuscles to action\nsnd granulates the corn at he root\nto that it drops out and hare* no\ntrace of scar or soreness.\nYou will also find \u201cCorn Fly Foot\nBath Powder* a boon far son. tired\nor (onpiring feet\n\"Corn Fbr for coma, lie. \u201cCoen\nFly Foot Bath Powder* Sc. and\n'Corn Fly Bunion Remedy* 50*. (all\n'hree\u201411.10 value\u2014 for 11.00)7 are\nsold under a positive moncy-lnct.\nguarantee by Hi-One Co, Newark,\nN. J, or local druggiat\nWorker*, the only miners vrmni\naatiee recignimet by the 4. P. at U\n\"Many organization* hasp re\npeated appealed fop affiliation!\nwith the Federation. iB r+eal or\nganization* have been tiddt 'It I*\nImpossible far yen to some in. Yon\nMost settle year differed*#* wit